		<div class="post" id="post-672">
			<h2>Kaiser Wilhelm II wants to be your friend on Facebook</h2>

			<div class="entry">
				<div class="tweetmeme_button" style="float: right; margin-left: 10px;"><iframe src="http://api.tweetmeme.com/button.js?url=http%3A%2F%2Fwww.daniellieberman.org%2F2010%2F05%2F12%2Fkaiser-wilhelm-ii-wants-to-be-your-friend-on-facebook%2F&amp;source=damfino11&amp;style=normal&amp;service=bit.ly&amp;space=20&amp;hashtags=Blogging,Cloud+Computing,Customer+Relations,Facebook,Google,Internet,Marketing,Social+Media&amp;b=2" height="61" width="50" frameborder="0" scrolling="no"></iframe></div>
<p><img class="alignleft" title="Kaiser Bill" src="http://t1.gstatic.com/images?q=tbn:7QT5rSKV8rLFnM:http://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/f/ff/Kaiser_Bill.jpg" alt="Kaiser Wilhelm" width="90" height="135" />George Carlin said that &#8220;military intelligence&#8221; is an oxymoron. Well, I don&#8217;t think so. Whatever we think about war (I imagine we can all agree that it&#8217;s not that great) and military forces (we probably concur that they have their problems),  war is a unique school; as the social institution at the sharp end of the stick,  a military must be an effective learning organization.</p>
<p>The U.S. Air Force has put together a Social Media Response Plan that is simple and systematic (it&#8217;s a <a title="Air Force Social Media Response Plan" href="http://www.daniellieberman.org/djlblog/wp-content/uploads/2010/05/AFD-091210-037.pdf">flowchart!</a>) and as Wild Apricot&#8217;s Non-Profit Technology blog counsels, go ahead and swipe it. I&#8217;m going to send it to all my clients who are worrying about how their going to handle the conversations that they don&#8217;t WANT to be having.</p>
<div class="shr-publisher-672"></div>
